<h2>Not Better, Not Worse — Different</h2>

<p>The temptation, on both sides, is to claim superiority. Eastern Christians can look at the West and see legalism, rationalism, and liturgical impoverishment. Western Christians can look at the East and see ethnic particularism, theological imprecision, and institutional dysfunction. Both caricatures contain grains of truth — and both are profoundly unfair.</p>

<p>The healthier posture is gratitude. The West gave the world the university, the hospital, the systematic defense of human rights, and a missionary energy that carried the Gospel to every continent. The East preserved the liturgy in its ancient fullness, developed a theology of the human person that anticipates modern psychology by a millennium, and produced a monastic tradition of breathtaking depth. Neither tradition is complete without the other.</p>

<p>John Paul II's image remains the best one: two lungs, one body. The Body of Christ needs both to breathe fully. And perhaps the greatest gift that Byzantine Catholics can offer the universal Church is precisely this: the daily, lived experience of holding East and West together — not in theory, but in worship, in prayer, and in the communion of saints.</p>

<p>In the final step, we'll turn from theology to practice — what it actually looks like to walk through the doors of a Byzantine Catholic church, and what you might find on the other side.</p>

